T1  - Monetary factors in the great depression
AU  - Hamilton, James D.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 19
IS  - 2
SP  - 145
EP  - 169
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/03/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(87)90045-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393287900456
AB  - This paper examines the role of monetary policy in the early stages of the Great Depression and considers the mechanism whereby this policy may have affected real activity. I conclude that the depression was preceded by a dramatic shift towards a highly contractionary monetary policy. The economic impact of this policy seems unlikely to have come through the conventional Keynesian channels of a shortage of liquidity and high ex ante real interest rates, but instead may have operated through unanticipated deflation, and, after 1930, through the disruption of financial intermediation as a consequence of the banking panics.
ER  - 

